00:54:23.060 --> 00:54:26.056
So academics, we
face pressure if we

00:54:26.056 --> 00:54:27.180
write about certain things.

00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:30.000
We have a fear of potentially
losing visa access.

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:32.582
In the grand scheme of things,
a visa is not a huge deal.

00:54:32.582 --> 00:54:33.540
We're going to be fine.

00:54:33.540 --> 00:54:35.880
But it's a
manifestation of that.

00:54:35.880 --> 00:54:39.060
Firms-- you might have read
about a lot of US airlines

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:43.710
now have been forced to change
their websites because they

00:54:43.710 --> 00:54:45.210
can no longer have
the word "Taiwan"

00:54:45.210 --> 00:54:48.280
on their website, because
Taiwan is a sensitive topic,

00:54:48.280 --> 00:54:50.010
and it's considered
part of China,

00:54:50.010 --> 00:54:51.685
according to the
Chinese government,

00:54:51.685 --> 00:54:52.560
and on and on and on.

00:54:52.560 --> 00:54:54.270
Cambridge University
Press is an example

00:54:54.270 --> 00:54:57.302
that's close to home for us.

00:54:57.302 --> 00:54:59.010
Cambridge University
Press runs a journal

00:54:59.010 --> 00:55:01.700
called "The China Quarterly,"
which is a China journal.

00:55:01.700 --> 00:55:03.600
At the pressure of the
Chinese government,

00:55:03.600 --> 00:55:05.325
last year-- or was
it two years ago?

00:55:05.325 --> 00:55:08.970
I can't remember-- they
removed upwards of 300 articles

00:55:08.970 --> 00:55:10.359
from their website in China.

00:55:10.359 --> 00:55:12.900
And the articles were all about
things like Tiananmen Square,

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:14.670
and Xinjiang, Tibet--

00:55:14.670 --> 00:55:16.660
sensitive topics.

00:55:16.660 --> 00:55:18.077
And this is alarming
because then,

00:55:18.077 --> 00:55:20.493
if you're a Chinese citizen,
and you're reading "The China

00:55:20.493 --> 00:55:22.650
Quarterly," you're getting
a sanitized version

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:23.760
of scholarship on China.

00:55:23.760 --> 00:55:26.299
You're getting a sanitized
version of history.

00:55:26.299 --> 00:55:28.590
And that's the version that
the party wants you to get.

00:55:28.590 --> 00:55:30.631
So fortunately, as a result
of academic pressure,

00:55:30.631 --> 00:55:32.820
we saw Cambridge
University Press eventually

00:55:32.820 --> 00:55:33.780
reverse its stance.

00:55:33.780 --> 00:55:36.950
But all of these individuals
are facing this decision.

00:55:36.950 --> 00:55:40.020
And it's a commonality actually
between firms, journalists,

00:55:40.020 --> 00:55:42.240
universities, and academics.

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:44.500
So that's one thing
that's alarming to me.

00:55:44.500 --> 00:55:48.270
Another thing that is
concerning is the monitoring

00:55:48.270 --> 00:55:50.910
that we used to see
reserved for China is now

00:55:50.910 --> 00:55:52.140
being extended overseas.

00:55:52.140 --> 00:55:54.600
So there are a lot
of Chinese students

00:55:54.600 --> 00:55:55.920
at American universities.

00:55:55.920 --> 00:55:58.260
And this is something we
need more research on,

00:55:58.260 --> 00:55:59.760
so I'm hesitant to
make a statement.

00:55:59.760 --> 00:56:01.980
But it seems, from
what I've heard,

00:56:01.980 --> 00:56:03.780
that there are many
Chinese students who

00:56:03.780 --> 00:56:06.374
feel that they are under the
same level of surveillance

00:56:06.374 --> 00:56:08.040
in an American classroom
than they would

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:09.464
be at a Chinese university.

00:56:09.464 --> 00:56:11.130
So I teach a course
on Chinese politics,

00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:13.380
and we talk about
sensitive topics.

00:56:13.380 --> 00:56:14.880
A Chinese student
in my course might

00:56:14.880 --> 00:56:16.740
feel reluctant to say
how they really feel

00:56:16.740 --> 00:56:18.450
or what they think about
the Chinese government

00:56:18.450 --> 00:56:20.460
because they're worried that
they might be being monitored,

00:56:20.460 --> 00:56:22.200
or that information
might make its way back

00:56:22.200 --> 00:56:23.158
to the Communist Party.

00:56:23.158 --> 00:56:26.670
So we are entering a phase where
Xi Jinping's assertiveness has

00:56:26.670 --> 00:56:29.160
now led the Communist
Party to try

00:56:29.160 --> 00:56:33.570
to influence discourse and
dialogue in other countries.

00:56:33.570 --> 00:56:36.150
And that's a trend that
I am worried about.

00:56:36.150 --> 00:56:37.590
Thank you for your question.

00:56:37.590 --> 00:56:38.090
Here.

00:56:38.090 --> 00:56:39.410
Yes.

00:56:39.410 --> 00:56:41.780
AUDIENCE: You partially
asked actually my question,

00:56:41.780 --> 00:56:43.980
but I want to extend the topic.

00:56:43.980 --> 00:56:47.300
You mentioned the influences
going abroad, but mainly

00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:49.910
focusing on Chinese citizens.

00:56:49.910 --> 00:56:54.320
What is influence globally
with other countries?

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:57.220
And do you see a
possible backfire

00:56:57.220 --> 00:56:59.570
and would other
countries trying to--

00:56:59.570 --> 00:57:02.760
how do I say-- interfere
with China's government issue

00:57:02.760 --> 00:57:04.040
and stuff?

00:57:04.040 --> 00:57:06.660
RORY TRUEX: So that's
a great question.

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:09.680
So for a long time, the
party rhetoric about this

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:11.480
was that China
does not interfere

00:57:11.480 --> 00:57:13.610
within the sovereign
affairs of other countries.

00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:14.440
That was the line.

00:57:14.440 --> 00:57:16.356
It's sort of this doctrine
of noninterference.

00:57:16.356 --> 00:57:18.499
Leave us alone, we'll
leave you alone.

00:57:18.499 --> 00:57:20.790
It's unclear whether we should
have believed that ever,

00:57:20.790 --> 00:57:24.230
but it's increasingly obvious
that they do interfere in some

00:57:24.230 --> 00:57:26.480
of the ways I just mentioned.

00:57:26.480 --> 00:57:29.240
More interestingly and
important to think about

00:57:29.240 --> 00:57:33.140
is this idea that the Chinese
system of governance itself

00:57:33.140 --> 00:57:35.934
could increasingly become a
model for other countries,

00:57:35.934 --> 00:57:37.850
particularly developing
countries, to emulate.

00:57:37.850 --> 00:57:39.427
This is the so-called
China model.

00:57:39.427 --> 00:57:41.510
And it means different
things to different people.

00:57:41.510 --> 00:57:44.420
But it's basically where you
have a system of authoritarian

00:57:44.420 --> 00:57:46.010
governments-- soft
authoritarianism,

00:57:46.010 --> 00:57:47.720
if we want to call it that,
although I don't know how soft

00:57:47.720 --> 00:57:48.530
it is--

00:57:48.530 --> 00:57:51.770
coupled with
state-led capitalism.

00:57:51.770 --> 00:57:55.109
And China has the record
of economic performance

00:57:55.109 --> 00:57:57.150
that is potentially
appealing to other countries.

00:57:57.150 --> 00:58:00.110
So it remains unclear
how much they're actually

00:58:00.110 --> 00:58:02.090
trying to shift
to the governance

00:58:02.090 --> 00:58:03.860
models of other countries.

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:05.540
I have a friend,
Maria Repnikova,

00:58:05.540 --> 00:58:08.450
who's a great political
scientist based

00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:09.764
at Georgia State.

00:58:09.764 --> 00:58:11.180
And she's doing
some work on this.

00:58:11.180 --> 00:58:13.490
And she's interviewing
officials throughout Africa,

00:58:13.490 --> 00:58:17.180
who are increasingly going
to China to be trained

00:58:17.180 --> 00:58:18.960
and to study
governance techniques

00:58:18.960 --> 00:58:21.720
from the Chinese system as
opposed to a Western system.

00:58:21.720 --> 00:58:24.080
So I think it's still
too early to tell

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:26.550
how much influence
there will be,

00:58:26.550 --> 00:58:29.370
but I think it will
likely increase.

00:58:29.370 --> 00:58:31.480
On that, I think I'm
actually out of time,

00:58:31.480 --> 00:58:33.350
so thank you all for
this opportunity.

00:58:33.350 --> 00:58:35.450
[APPLAUSE]

00:58:35.450 --> 00:58:37.300
Thank you.

